you need to use `sys.argv` inside `main` to access command line arguments.

```python
import sys

def main(args=None):
    if args is None:
        args = sys.argv[1:]
    print(args)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

Jason, thanks for bringing this up. We are not going to change our bundled pip/setuptools wheels, but we can workaround on our side: I have opened up a bug in Jython to support isolated surrogates, just so we can avoid this problem in this and other libraries http://bugs.jython.org/issue2340. I'd like to see this completed for Jython 2.7.1. The key of this approach will be to UCS4 encoding, plus forbidding interoperation with Java:

```
    @Override
    public Object __tojava__(Class<?> c) {
        if (c.isAssignableFrom(String.class)) {
	        throw Py.TypeError("Cannot convert unicode with isolated surrogates to Java");
        }
	return super.__tojava__(c);
    }
```

I just started playing with this idea, using a hacky approach, and it seems to work: in Python code only, it's fine, and when it hits Java calls, it fails cleanly with a `TypeError`. A clean approach per https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0393/ is probably the way to go.

